Tim Berners-Lee, World Wide Network creator, is creating a company that aims to rival Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of technology legend, ‘Inrupt,' is a company built from the Berners-Lee open-source platform called 'Solid'.
‘Solid' allows users to choose where their data is stored and which persons are allowed to access certain information.
In an exclusive interview for ‘Fast Company,' Berners-Lee joked that the goal behind ‘Inrupt' is "world domination."
"We have to do it now," he said of this innovative company.
"It's a historic moment."
The application uses Solid technology to allow people to create "store up their personal data on the grid" or a POD.
It may contain contact lists, lists of things to do, musical lists and other personal and professional tools.
It's like having Google Drive available in a browser at the same time, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spiffy.
What is unique to the storage of personal data on the network is the fact that it remains completely in the hands of users what kind of information will access.
The company calls this "personal power through data."
The idea for Inrup, according to the company's executive director, John Bruce, is to bring together the resources, processes and skills needed to help Solid be available to everyone.
