National Trust Watches Secret Life of Bats
A new research being carried out by a company in mountainous areas of Scotland aims to find out how bats use the terrain to hunt for food.
It is hoped that the new findings will shed new light on the behaviour of unique flying mammals and will assist protective activities in the future.
Research by scientists at the National Trust for Scotland will follow the common bats and what are called the soprano pipistrallas, as well as the brown ears and Daubon bats in the Inverwee gardens, at Western Ross.
Special recording equipment will be placed at key points throughout the area to track bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct field studies using hand detectors.
The analysis of the sounds to be carried out by experts for all recordings will determine the frequency of bat sounds and what each species does.
Later, a report will be drawn up and a map of their habitat to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation consultant for NTS, hopes that the conclusions will show which habitats are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information would help determine settlement management goods, such as creating pasture grounds and maintaining forests for bats and other related species.
The number of bats in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom has dropped dramatically over the past century.
They are under threat of construction and developmental work that can affect nests and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting may also pose a risk, as do sticky letters or chemical components of building materials, as well as domestic animal attacks.
The bats aren't really blind.
However, because of their nighttime hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching a cut.
They use a sophisticated technique of finding location through sounds to determine insects and obstacles in flight with accuracy.
The NTS, which is responsible for caring for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 760,000 hectares of land in the country, is very serious about bats.
There are ten trained experts who regularly conduct studies, nest inspections, and sometimes engage in rescue programs.
The organisation has even set up the first and only reserve in Scotland dedicated to bats in Threave, Dumfrieds and Galloway, which serves as home to eight of Scotland’s ten bat species.
The manager of this reserve, David Thompson, says this place is the ideal territory for them.
"Here at Threave we have an excellent area for bats," he said.
"We have old buildings, many ancient trees and all the right habitat.
But there's still a lot about bats that remain unknown, so the work we do here and in other places will help us to understand more what they need to be ‘developed'."
It highlights the importance of performing bat control before performing property maintenance because there is the possibility that the unintentional destruction of a nest could kill up to 400 female bats and young people, killing the entire population of an area.
The bats of the night are protected, and the murder, and the harassment, or the destruction of their nests, are illegal.
Elizabeth Ferrell, Scottish employee of the Trust for the Preservation of the Bats of Night, encourages people to become part of the relief effort.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and many of our species, we just don't know how their population is moving."
