Syria is 'ready' for refugee returns, says foreign minister
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and is appealing for help to rebuild the country destroyed by a war that has lasted for more than seven years.
Speaking at the UN General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moalem said conditions in the country are improving.
"Today, the situation in the country is much more stable and secure thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism," he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate areas destroyed by terrorists to restore normality.
Currently, there are all conditions for the voluntary return of refugees to their country, where they had to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures that hit their daily lives and their well - being.
The UN estimates that about 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the beginning of the war in 2011.
About six million others still living in the country need humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moalem said the Syrian regime would welcome help to rebuild the destroyed state.
He stressed, however, that the country will not accept assistance or conditional assistance from countries that sponsored the uprising.
